{"title_page": "Grenelle agreements", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{one source|date=June 2013}}\nThe '''Grenelle Agreements''' ({{lang-fr|Accords de Grenelle}}) or '''Grenelle Reports''' were negotiated 25 and 26 May, during the crisis of [[May 1968 in France]] by the representative of the [[Georges Pompidou|Pompidou]] government, the [[List of trade unions in France|trade unions]], and the {{ill|Organisation patronale fran\u00e7aise|fr}}. Among the negotiators were [[Jacques Chirac]], then the young [[Secretary of State]] of Local Affairs, and [[Georges S\u00e9guy]], representative of the [[Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration g\u00e9n\u00e9rale du travail]].\n\nThe Grenelle Agreements, concluded 27 May 1968\u2014but not signed\u2014led to a 35% increase in the [[minimum wage]] (salaire minimum interprofessionnel garanti) and 10% increase in average [[real wage]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Michael |last=Seidman |title=Workers in a Repressive Society of Seductions: Parisian Metallurgists in May\u2013June 1968 |work=French Historical Studies |volume=18 |issue=1 |date=1993 |page=264 |publisher=Duke University Press |location=Durham |doi=10.2307/286966 |hdl= |isbn= |issn=0016-1071 |jstor=286966 |oclc=5548695526}}</ref> It also provided for the establishment of the trade union section of business (''{{ill|Section syndicale d'entreprise|fr}}''), through the [[Statute|act]] of 27 December 1968.\n\nRejected by the base, the agreements did not immediately solve the social crisis and the strikes continued. But three days later on 30 May, [[Charles de Gaulle]], back in Paris after meeting with [[Jacques Massu]] in [[Baden-Baden]], [[Germany]], the previous day, was comforted by an enormous Gaullist counter-demonstration on Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es. He decided to dissolve the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] and to call for elections on 30 June 1968. The triumph of the Gaullists of the [[Union pour la nouvelle R\u00e9publique|UDR]] (293 of 378 seats) ended the political crisis.\n\nThe name Grenelle is taken from the area where the agreements were negotiated, at the [[Minister of Social Affairs (France)|Ministry of Social Affairs]] located on the {{ill|rue de Grenelle|fr}} in Paris. The hotel, built in the late 18th century, formerly the Archbishop's Palace, was actually part of the Ministry of Labour since 1905. The \"Room of Agreements\", named since then, is an old dining room decorated in 18th-century style has been preserved.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Grenelle de l'environnement]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Labor history of France]]\n[[Category:May 1968 events in France]]\n[[Category:1968 documents]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{one source|date=June 2013}}\nThe '''Grenelle Agreements''' ({{lang-fr|Accords de Grenelle}}) or '''Grenelle Reports''' were negotiated 25 and 26 May, during the crisis of [[May 1968 in France]] by the representative of the [[Georges Pompidou|Pompidou]] government, the [[List of trade unions in France|trade unions]], and the {{ill|Organisation patronale fran\u00e7aise|fr}}. Among the negotiators were [[Jacques Chirac]], then the young [[Secretary of State]] of Local Affairs, and {{ill|Georges S\u00e9guy|fr}}, representative of the [[Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration g\u00e9n\u00e9rale du travail]].\n\nThe Grenelle Agreements, concluded 27 May 1968\u2014but not signed\u2014led to a 35% increase in the [[minimum wage]] (salaire minimum interprofessionnel garanti) and 10% increase in average [[real wage]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Michael |last=Seidman |title=Workers in a Repressive Society of Seductions: Parisian Metallurgists in May\u2013June 1968 |work=French Historical Studies |volume=18 |issue=1 |date=1993 |page=264 |publisher=Duke University Press |location=Durham |doi=10.2307/286966 |hdl= |isbn= |issn=0016-1071 |jstor=286966 |oclc=5548695526}}</ref> It also provided for the establishment of the trade union section of business (''{{ill|Section syndicale d'entreprise|fr}}''), through the [[Statute|act]] of 27 December 1968.\n\nRejected by the base, the agreements did not immediately solve the social crisis and the strikes continued. But three days later on 30 May, [[Charles de Gaulle]], back in Paris after meeting with [[Jacques Massu]] in [[Baden-Baden]], [[Germany]], the previous day, was comforted by an enormous Gaullist counter-demonstration on Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es. He decided to dissolve the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] and to call for elections on 30 June 1968. The triumph of the Gaullists of the [[Union pour la nouvelle R\u00e9publique|UDR]] (293 of 378 seats) ended the political crisis.\n\nThe name Grenelle is taken from the area where the agreements were negotiated, at the [[Minister of Social Affairs (France)|Ministry of Social Affairs]] located on the {{ill|rue de Grenelle|fr}} in Paris. The hotel, built in the late 18th century, formerly the Archbishop's Palace, was actually part of the Ministry of Labour since 1905. The \"Room of Agreements\", named since then, is an old dining room decorated in 18th-century style has been preserved.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Grenelle de l'environnement]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Labor history of France]]\n[[Category:May 1968 events in France]]\n[[Category:1968 documents]]\n", "name_user": "Warofdreams", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grenelle_agreements"}
{"title_page": "Samuel Prescott", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Samuel Prescott\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = August 19, 1751\n| birth_place = [[Concord, Massachusetts]], [[British America]]\n| death_date  = between  November 23, 1776 and December 26, 1777\n| death_place = Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada\n| occupation  = Surgeon, Express courier\n| networth =\n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| residence   =\n| alma_mater  =\n| website     =\n| signature   = \n}}\n\n'''Samuel Prescott''' (August 19, 1751 \u2013 c. 1777) was a doctor and a [[Province of Massachusetts Bay|Massachusetts]] [[Patriot (American Revolution)|Patriot]] during the [[American Revolutionary War]].  He is best known for his role in [[Paul Revere]]'s \"midnight ride\" to warn the townspeople of [[Concord, Massachusetts]] of the impending British army move to capture guns and gunpowder kept there at the beginning of the American Revolution. He was the only participant in the ride to reach Concord.\n\n== Early life ==\n[[File:Jonathan Prescott, Chester, Nova Scotia.png|thumb|Samuel Prescott's uncle [[Jonathan Prescott (military officer)|Jonathan Prescott]]]]\nDr. Samuel Prescott was born August 19, 1751.  He lived in colonial [[Concord, Massachusetts]], among his large extended family. (His uncle was [[Jonathan Prescott (military officer)|Jonathan Prescott]].)  Indeed, the Prescotts and their extended family played an important and often heroic<!--more POV that may be self-serving--> role in colonial history.  These include settling concord, fighting in colonial wars, and negotiating for the ransom of [[Mary Rowlandson]].<ref>Caes, 34, wherein regarding Rowlandson the reference is to John Hoar, father of the second wife of Capt. Jonathan Prescott (d. 1721). Captain Jonathan was Samuel Prescott's great grandfather.</ref>\n\nPrescott followed in the footsteps of his older brother Benjamin and apprenticed under his father, Abel Prescott, for about seven years. He did open a practice in Concord, just before or after which time he began to court Lydia Mulliken, daughter of a well-respected Lexington clockmaker who had died in 1767.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=D. Michael Ryan|url=http://www.concordma.com/magazine/julaug01/samuelprescott.html|title=The Tale of Two Families Joined by Love, Shattered by War|accessdate=24 July 2009|work=Concord Magazine|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724051850/http://www.concordma.com/magazine/julaug01/samuelprescott.html|archivedate=24 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring the latter part of his [[apprenticeship]] or shortly after he began his medical practice, he became an active member in the [[Patriot (American Revolution)|patriot movement]]. There is strong circumstantial evidence that he was an express courier for the [[Sons of Liberty]] and the [[Committees of Correspondence]], and that he was an important liaison between the Concord Defense Committee and [[John Hancock]] and other leaders of the patriots.<ref>Caes, 206</ref>\n\n== The Ride ==\nOn the evening of April 18, 1775, [[Paul Revere]] and [[William Dawes]] were dispatched by [[Joseph Warren]] to warn the countryside that the British were coming. Prescott was in Lexington at the time to visit with his fianc\u00e9e, Lydia Mulliken.<ref>Prescott, 66</ref> He was also there to report on Concord's readiness, its status in hiding supplies and munitions from the British, and its success in moving cannon to Groton lest it fall into British hands.<ref>Wheildon, 7</ref> The British wanted the military stores at Concord and had hoped to capture [[Samuel Adams]] and John Hancock in the process.{{Citation needed|date = April 2017}}\n\nWhen Prescott left Lexington, it was about 1 a.m. the next morning, April 19.  On his way back to Concord he met Paul Revere and William Dawes, who had just left Lexington shortly before him and were also on their way to Concord\u2014to warn the town that the Redcoats were on the march.<ref>Dawes, 89, but this is taken, as cited in his book, from  Revere's deposition for Reverend Jerry Belknap, founder of the Massachusetts Historical Society. Revere actually produced three versions of the deposition, two in 1775 and one in 1798, but they are not contradictory though they are of varying lengths.</ref>\n\nWhen the three continued on to Hartwell's tavern in the lower bounds of Lincoln, they were cut off by four British horseman who were part of a larger scouting party sent out the preceding evening.  Revere was captured but both Prescott and Dawes succeeded in escaping.  Prescott did so with a show of artful horsemanship and knowledge of the forest. Prescott emerged at [[Hartwell Tavern]], awakened Ephraim Hartwell, and informed him of the pending arrival of the British soldiers. Hartwell sent his black slave, Violet, down the road to alert his parents, Samuel and Mary. His mother then relayed the message to Captain William Smith, commanding officer of the Lincoln minutemen. The minutemen received the noticed in time, and arrived at Old North Bridge before their enemy. Prescott then made his way to Concord.<ref name=nps>[https://www.nps.gov/mima/hartwell-tavern.htm The Historic Hartwell Tavern] - NPS.gov</ref>\n\nDawes also escaped from his pursuers, but it was after a close chase, a frantic ruse on his part, and a bit of luck. Once he was safe, he considered circling around the patrol and racing on to Concord much as Prescott had, but he heard the Concord town house bell and knew Prescott had made it there, and so he continued on his special mission, for he was only assigned to accompany Revere to Concord.<ref>Dawes, 119</ref> Prescott, meanwhile, continued west to warn Acton, Massachusetts while his brother [[Abel Prescott, Jr.]] rode south to warn [[Sudbury, Massachusetts|Sudbury]] and [[Framingham, Massachusetts|Framingham]].  By this time, countless riders were also dispatched from other towns to spread the warning\u2014while bells and cannon were rung or fired to punctuate the danger at hand.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}\n\nBecause of  the \"midnight\" rides of Revere, Dawes, Prescott, and many other expresses (couriers), [[minutemen]] and [[militia]] everywhere were on the ready, many marching to Concord to effectively engage the British Army at the Battles of Lexington and Concord. Prescott was there to witness the [[Battle of Concord]], then tried to beat the British back to Lexington to see Lydia Mulliken and her family and to help with the wounded.<ref>Caes, 248\u2013253</ref>  He remained at Lexington as a volunteer surgeon for about two weeks, then seems to have disappeared into the war.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}\n\n[[File:Concord Expedition and Patriot Messengers.jpg|thumb|center|800px|A [[National Park Service]] map showing the route of the initial [[Patriot (American Revolution)|Patriot]] messengers including Prescott (purple trail)]]\n\n== Prescott's life following \"The Ride\" ==\nThere is evidence that Prescott went on to serve as a surgeon in the [[Continental Army]], a tradition that he joined the crew of a New England [[privateer]], and a report that he was in prison in [[City of Halifax|Halifax, Nova Scotia]], where he may have died between  November 23, 1776 and December 26 (1777?).<ref>There is only hearsay of the privateering, and Caes provides other alternatives, beginning with the Battles of Breed's and Bunker Hills at which he lists a number of Samuel's relatives (some through marriage) who fought there.</ref>  There is also circumstantial evidence that he served in some medical support capacity out of [[Fort Ticonderoga]] during the invasion attempts against Canada and until about the time of [[Benedict Arnold]]'s failed attempts against [[Sir Guy Carleton]] on [[Lake Champlain]].<ref>Speculations of which appear in ''Legend''</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nPrescott's ride is re-enacted every [[Patriots' Day]] eve (observed) in the Town of Acton. The re-enactment begins in East Acton, continues through Acton Center, and ends at Liberty Tree Farm, where once was the home of a minuteman named Simon Hunt. The distance is approximately five miles (8&nbsp;km).\n\nThere are also re-enactments on Patriots' Day (usually the third Monday of April) of the rides of William Dawes and Paul Revere, to commemorate the famous \"midnight\" ride that began in the evening hours of April 18 and continued on April 19.\n\nPrescott's ride is re-enacted every year at midnight April 18\u201319 at Concord's First Parish Church. The re-enactment is preceded by a Patriots' Ball.  The Minute Men march with fife and drum leading the attendees from the armory to the church. The Captain of the Concord Minute Men reads a message handed him by \"Prescott\" on horseback.\n\nA memorial plaque to Prescott is at his former home in Concord, Massachusetts.<ref>[http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMA7Q_Home_of_Dr_Samuel_Prescott waymarking.com]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Liberty's Kids]]''\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{Cite book|last=Caes|first=Charles J.|year=2009|title=Legend of the Third Horseman: Life and Times of Dr. Samuel Prescott, the Man Who Finished the Midnight Ride of Paul Revere|publisher=Bloomington, IND: Xlibris}}{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=December 2017}}\n* [https://salinabakerauthor.com/2017/01/22/the-man-who-finished-the-midnight-ride-of-paul-revere-and-william-dawes/  The Man Who Finished The Midnight Ride of Paul Revere and William Dawes]\n* {{Cite book|last=Dawes|first=C. Burr|year=1975|title=William Dawes: First Rider for Revolution|publisher=Newark, Ohio: History Gardens Press}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Prescott|first=William MD.|year=1872|title=The Prescott Memorial or Genealogical Memoir of the Prescott Families In America.|publisher=Ashville, N.C.: Ward Press (1983)}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Wheildon|first=William C.|year=1885|title=New Chapter in the History of the Concord Fight: Groton Minute-Men at the North Bridge, April 18\u201319, 1775.|publisher=Boston: Lee & Shepard}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Marvin|first=Abijah P.|year=1879|title=History of the Town of Lancaster, Massachusetts: from first settlement to the present time 1643\u20131879.|publisher=The Town of Lancaster, Massachusetts}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Selesky|first=H. E.|year=2006|title=History of the Town of Lancaster, Massachusetts: from first settlement to the present time 1643\u20131879.|publisher=The Town of Lancaster, Massachusetts}}\n\n<!--\n== External links ==\n-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prescott, Samuel}}\n[[Category:1751 births]]\n[[Category:1777 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Revolutionary War deaths]]\n[[Category:American surgeons]]\n[[Category:People from Concord, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People of Massachusetts in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Physicians in the American Revolution]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Samuel Prescott\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = August 19, 1751\n| birth_place = [[Concord, Massachusetts]], [[British America]]\n| death_date  = between  November 23, 1776 and December 26, 1777\n| death_place = Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada\n| occupation  = Surgeon, Express courier\n| networth =\n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| residence   =\n| alma_mater  =\n| website     =\n| signature   = \n}}\n\n'''Samuel Prescott''' (August 19, 1751 \u2013 c. 1777) was a doctor and  a[[Province of Massachusetts Bay|Massachusetts]] [[Patriot (American Revolution)|Patriot]] during the [[American Revolutionary War]].  He is best known for his role in [[Paul Revere]]'s \"midnight ride\" to warn the townspeople of [[Concord, Massachusetts]] of the impending British army move to capture guns and gunpowder kept there at the beginning of the American Revolution. He was the only participant in the ride to reach Concord.\n\n== Early life ==\n[[File:Jonathan Prescott, Chester, Nova Scotia.png|thumb|Samuel Prescott's uncle [[Jonathan Prescott (military officer)|Jonathan Prescott]]]]\nDr. Samuel Prescott was born August 19, 1751.  He lived in colonial [[Concord, Massachusetts]], among his large extended family. (His uncle was [[Jonathan Prescott (military officer)|Jonathan Prescott]].)  Indeed, the Prescotts and their extended family played an important and often heroic<!--more POV that may be self-serving--> role in colonial history.  These include settling concord, fighting in colonial wars, and negotiating for the ransom of [[Mary Rowlandson]].<ref>Caes, 34, wherein regarding Rowlandson the reference is to John Hoar, father of the second wife of Capt. Jonathan Prescott (d. 1721). Captain Jonathan was Samuel Prescott's great grandfather.</ref>\n\nPrescott followed in the footsteps of his older brother Benjamin and apprenticed under his father, Abel Prescott, for about seven years. He did open a practice in Concord, just before or after which time he began to court Lydia Mulliken, daughter of a well-respected Lexington clockmaker who had died in 1767.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=D. Michael Ryan|url=http://www.concordma.com/magazine/julaug01/samuelprescott.html|title=The Tale of Two Families Joined by Love, Shattered by War|accessdate=24 July 2009|work=Concord Magazine|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724051850/http://www.concordma.com/magazine/julaug01/samuelprescott.html|archivedate=24 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring the latter part of his [[apprenticeship]] or shortly after he began his medical practice, he became an active member in the [[Patriot (American Revolution)|patriot movement]]. There is strong circumstantial evidence that he was an express courier for the [[Sons of Liberty]] and the [[Committees of Correspondence]], and that he was an important liaison between the Concord Defense Committee and [[John Hancock]] and other leaders of the patriots.<ref>Caes, 206</ref>\n\n== The Ride ==\nOn the evening of April 18, 1775, [[Paul Revere]] and [[William Dawes]] were d