{"title_page": "Robert Kerr, 1st Earl of Ancram", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2019}}\n[[File:1st Earl of Ancram.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Robert Kerr, 1st Earl of Ancram by [[Jan Lievens]]<ref>[http://www.nationalgalleries.org/collection/online_az/4:322/result/0/8758?initial=L&artistId=2993&artistName=Jan%20Lievens&submit=1 Jan Lievens portrait of Robert Kerr] in the [[National Galleries of Scotland]]</ref>]]\n'''Sir Robert Kerr (or Carr), 1st Earl of Ancram''' (c. 1578\u20131654), was a Scottish nobleman, English politician and writer.<ref name=Chambers1840>Chambers, Robert (1840), [https://books.google.com/books?id=0iopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA315#v=onepage&q=&f=false A biographical dictionary of eminent Scotsmen], Volume 3, Blackie and Son, pp 315-6. </ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe descended from a third son of Sir Andrew Kerr of [[Ferniehirst Castle|Ferniehurst]], and was laird of [[Ancrum]] in [[Roxburghshire]]. He was born about 1578, and succeeded to the family estate in 1590 on the death of his father, who was assassinated by his kinsman, Robert Ker, younger of [[Cessford Castle|Cessford]]. He was cousin to [[Robert Carr, Earl of Somerset|Robert Carr]], the [[favourite]] of [[James I of England|James VI]]. Kerr appears to have also been honoured at an early age with court favour. Soon after the king's accession to the English throne, Kerr occupied a considerable station in the household of [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]]. He subsequently was employed by [[Charles I of England|Prince Charles]], who became his patron through life. Charles mediated the marriage between Sir Robert and the [[Anne Stanley, Countess of Ancram|Lady Anne Stanley]], daughter of the [[William Stanley, 6th Earl of Derby|Earl of Derby]].<ref name=Chambers1840/>\n\nIn 1620, Kerr was involved in a fatal quarrel with Charles Maxwell, who insinuated that he had slighted the [[George Villiers, 1st Duke of Buckingham|Duke of Buckingham]] and insulted him without provocation as he entered the palace at [[Newmarket, Suffolk|Newmarket]]. In a duel that followed, Sir Robert killed Maxwell. Even though Maxwell's friends acquitted Kerr of blame, the king's strict rules for prevention and punishment of duels forced him to flee to Holland, where he remained about a year. During his exile, he collected pictures, for which, like his royal master, he had good taste. He eventually presented those he brought back with him to the prince. He was also distinguished by his literary taste and was a friend of [[John Donne]].<ref name=Chambers1840/> He also lived in [[Whitehall Palace]] and [[Kew]].\n\nOn the accession of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] to the throne, in 1625, Sir Robert Kerr was made a [[gentleman of the bedchamber]].\n\nHe was [[Member of Parliament|Member]] of [[Parliament of England|Parliament]] (MP) for [[Aylesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Aylesbury]] in 1625, and for [[Lostwithiel (UK Parliament constituency)|Lostwithiel]] and [[Preston (UK Parliament constituency)|Preston]] in 1628.<ref name=HoP>http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/kerr-sir-robert-1578-1654</ref>\n\nOn 24 June 1633, when Charles was in Scotland at his coronation, Kerr was elevated to the peerage under the titles [[Earl of Ancram]] and Lord Kerr of Nisbet, Langnewton, and Dolphinstoun.<ref>David Laing, ''Correspondence of Sir Robert Kerr, first Earl of Ancram'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1875), p. xviii.</ref> Previously, his son William, by his first wife Elizabeth, daughter of Sir John Murray of [[Blackbarony]], had married his relative, Anne, [[Marquess of Lothian|Countess of Lothian]] in her own right, and had been, by the king, given the title [[Marquess of Lothian|Earl of Lothian]].<ref>David Laing, ''Correspondence of Sir Robert Kerr, first Earl of Ancram'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1875), pp. xlviii, li.</ref> It was therefore arranged, in the patent granted to Kerr, that his own title should descend to the children of his second marriage. Thus, he was father of two peers.<ref name=Chambers1840/>\n\nUnlike others who owed everything to this prince, the Earl of Ancram remained the prince's steady adherent during the whole of his troubles\u2014though he was unable to prevent his eldest son, the [[William Kerr, 3rd Earl of Lothian|Earl of Lothian]], from acting a conspicuous part on the opposite side. On the death of King Charles, Kerr took refuge in Holland, where he spent the remainder of his days in solitary afflictions and poverty, and died in 1654, aged 76. [[Jan Lievens]] painted him marvelously.\n\nHis son [[Charles Carr, 2nd Earl of Ancram|Charles]], inherited his title, but ultimately merged with that of Lothian.<ref name=Chambers1840/>\n\n==Family==\nHe had two sons by his first marriage to Elizabeth Murray:\n*Stanley Kerr (d. bef. May 1672){{citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n*[[William Kerr, 1st Earl of Lothian]](bef. 1615&nbsp;\u2013 c. October 1675)\n\nHe had one son and two daughters by his second marriage to [[Anne Stanley, Countess of Ancram|Anne]], daughter of [[William Stanley, 6th Earl of Derby]]:{{citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n*[[Charles Kerr, 2nd Earl of Ancram]] (6 August 1624&nbsp;\u2013 September 1690)\n*Vere Kerr\n*Elizabeth Kerr\n\n==References==\n{{source-attribution|\"A biographical dictionary of eminent Scotsmen\", Robert Chambers (1840)}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Earl of Ancram]]\n  | years  = 1633\u20131654\n  | before = New creation\n  | after  = [[Charles Kerr, 2nd Earl of Ancram|Charles Kerr]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ancram, Robert Kerr, 1st Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1578 births]]\n[[Category:1654 deaths]]\n[[Category:Earls of Ancram]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Duellists]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish writers]]\n[[Category:People of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:People from Roxburgh]]\n[[Category:People from Surrey]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1625]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1628\u20131629]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2019}}\n[[File:1st Earl of Ancram.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Robert Kerr, 1st Earl of Ancram by [[Jan Lievens]]<ref>[http://www.nationalgalleries.org/collection/online_az/4:322/result/0/8758?initial=L&artistId=2993&artistName=Jan%20Lievens&submit=1 Jan Lievens portrait of Robert Kerr] in the [[National Galleries of Scotland]]</ref>]]\n'''Sir Robert Kerr (or Carr), 1st Earl of Ancram''' (c. 1578\u20131654), was a Scottish nobleman, English politician and writer.<ref name=Chambers1840>Chambers, Robert (1840), [https://books.google.com/books?id=0iopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA315#v=onepage&q=&f=false A biographical dictionary of eminent Scotsmen], Volume 3, Blackie and Son, pp 315-6. </ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe descended from a third son of Sir Andrew Kerr of [[Ferniehirst Castle|Ferniehurst]], and was laird of [[Ancrum]] in [[Roxburghshire]]. He was born about 1578, and succeeded to the family estate in 1590 on the death of his father, who was assassinated by his kinsman, Robert Ker, younger of [[Cessford Castle|Cessford]]. He was cousin to [[Robert Carr, Earl of Somerset|Robert Carr]], the [[favourite]] of [[James I of England|James VI]]. Kerr appears to have also been honoured at an early age with court favour. Soon after the king's accession to the English throne, Kerr occupied a considerable station in the household of [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]]. He subsequently was employed by [[Charles I of England|Prince Charles]], who became his patron through life. Charles mediated the marriage between Sir Robert and the [[Anne Stanley, Countess of Ancram|Lady Anne Stanley]], daughter of the [[William Stanley, 6th Earl of Derby|Earl of Derby]].<ref name=Chambers1840/>\n\nIn 1620, Kerr was involved in a fatal quarrel with Charles Maxwell, who insinuated that he had slighted the [[George Villiers, 1st Duke of Buckingham|Duke of Buckingham]] and insulted him without provocation as he entered the palace at [[Newmarket, Suffolk|Newmarket]]. In a duel that followed, Sir Robert killed Maxwell. Even though Maxwell's friends acquitted Kerr of blame, the king's strict rules for prevention and punishment of duels forced him to flee to Holland, where he remained about a year. During his exile, he collected pictures, for which, like his royal master, he had good taste. He eventually presented those he brought back with him to the prince. He was also distinguished by his literary taste and was a friend of [[John Donne]].<ref name=Chambers1840/> He also lived in [[Whitehall Palace]] and [[Kew]].\n\nOn the accession of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] to the throne, in 1625, Sir Robert Kerr was made a [[gentleman of the bedchamber]].\n\nHe was [[Member of Parliament|Member]] of [[Parliament of England|Parliament]] (MP) for [[Aylesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Aylesbury]] in 1625, and for [[Lostwithiel (UK Parliament constituency)|Lostwithiel]] and [[Preston (UK Parliament constituency)|Preston]] in 1628.<ref name=HoP>http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/kerr-sir-robert-1578-1654</ref>\n\nOn 24 June 1633, when Charles was in Scotland at his coronation, Kerr was elevated to the peerage under the titles [[Earl of Ancram]] and Lord Kerr of Nisbet, Langnewton, and Dolphinstoun.<ref>David Laing, ''Correspondence of Sir Robert Kerr, first Earl of Ancram'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1875), p. xviii.</ref> Previously, his son William, by his first wife Elizabeth, daughter of Sir John Murray of [[Blackbarony]], had married his relative, Anne, [[Marquess of Lothian|Countess of Lothian]] in her own right, and had been, by the king, given the title [[Earl of Lothian]].<ref>David Laing, ''Correspondence of Sir Robert Kerr, first Earl of Ancram'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1875), pp. xlviii, li.</ref> It was therefore arranged, in the patent granted to Kerr, that his own title should descend to the children of his second marriage. Thus, he was father of two peers.<ref name=Chambers1840/>\n\nUnlike others who owed everything to this prince, the Earl of Ancram remained the prince's steady adherent during the whole of his troubles\u2014though he was unable to prevent his eldest son, the [[William Kerr, 3rd Earl of Lothian|Earl of Lothian]], from acting a conspicuous part on the opposite side. On the death of King Charles, Kerr took refuge in Holland, where he spent the remainder of his days in solitary afflictions and poverty, and died in 1654, aged 76. [[Jan Lievens]] painted him marvelously.\n\nHis son [[Charles Carr, 2nd Earl of Ancram|Charles]], inherited his title, but ultimately merged with that of Lothian.<ref name=Chambers1840/>\n\n==Family==\nHe had two sons by his first marriage to Elizabeth Murray:\n*Stanley Kerr (d. bef. May 1672){{citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n*[[William Kerr, 1st Earl of Lothian]](bef. 1615&nbsp;\u2013 c. October 1675)\n\nHe had one son and two daughters by his second marriage to [[Anne Stanley, Countess of Ancram|Anne]], daughter of [[William Stanley, 6th Earl of Derby]]:{{citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n*[[Charles Kerr, 2nd Earl of Ancram]] (6 August 1624&nbsp;\u2013 September 1690)\n*Vere Kerr\n*Elizabeth Kerr\n\n==References==\n{{source-attribution|\"A biographical dictionary of eminent Scotsmen\", Robert Chambers (1840)}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Earl of Ancram]]\n  | years  = 1633\u20131654\n  | before = New creation\n  | after  = [[Charles Kerr, 2nd Earl of Ancram|Charles Kerr]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ancram, Robert Kerr, 1st Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1578 births]]\n[[Category:1654 deaths]]\n[[Category:Earls of Ancram]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Duellists]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish writers]]\n[[Category:People of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:People from Roxburgh]]\n[[Category:People from Surrey]]\n[[Category: